  "narrative": {
    "intro": "NAICS 336412 federal contract obligations total $4.2B in FY2026 to date. Obligations were down 65.0% year over year, with 6,807 awards and an average award size of $619K; current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date). Annual obligations have varied: FY21 was $7.3B, FY22 was $11.1B, FY23 was $13.7B, FY24 was $8.4B, FY25 was $12B, and FY26 is $4.2B. The Department of Defense accounted for the vast majority of FY2026 to date buying at $4.1B, while other agencies recorded much smaller obligations such as Department of Homeland Security at $74M and Department of Commerce at $5.4M. Vendor concentration is high among a few large suppliers: RTX CORPORATION at $1.2B and GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY entries at $1.1B and $416M are the largest single-vendor obligations in FY2026 to date. Contracting activity this fiscal year to date shows a marked decline in total obligations compared with prior peak years, while award counts and average award size reflect the current mix of smaller and larger actions across agencies.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How did NAICS 336412 obligations change over time?",
        "body": "Obligations peaked in FY23 at $13.7B and then moved to $8.4B in FY24 and $12B in FY25 before falling to $4.2B in FY26 to date. Year-over-year obligations fell 65.0%, reflecting the FY26 to date total of $4.2B compared with prior full-year levels."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Who are the largest buyers and vendors in FY2026 to date?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense is the largest buyer at $4.1B, with other agencies such as Department of Homeland Security at $74M and Department of Commerce at $5.4M far behind. The largest vendors are RTX CORPORATION at $1.2B and GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY at $1.1B and $416M, followed by ROLLS-ROYCE CORPORATION at $553M and THE BOEING COMPANY at $273M."
      }
    ]
